            <creation>This story, with the short title "Bahor and His Son Encounter a Thief," is recent: the earliest PEMM manuscript* in which this story appears is from around <date>1875</date>.Originally composed in <placeName ref="LOC3010Ethiop">Ethiopia</placeName></creation>
            <abstract>
                <p>In Cairo there lived a poor man named Bhor. Though he didn’t know the ways of the world, he loved Mary. A sinner named Demas decided to take advantage of this man naïveté and hatched a plot in which he stole the townspeople’s possessions and blamed the theft on Bhor. When the townspeople prayed for Mary to help them catch the thief, Demas spoke up and blamed the theft on Bhor. A message suddenly appeared on Demas’s forehead revealing him to be the true thief. Meanwhile, Bhor, along with his son Laeka Maryam, had messages on their foreheads identifying them to be servants of God and Mary.</p>
            </abstract>
